# Robot & Field Absolute Positioning
Documented by: Anton

Date: 11/25/18


### Goal
Normal convention in coding autonomous is to give the robot directions relative to the current position.

ex: `move 10 inches forward, then rotate 90 degrees clockwise`


This is great, but it becomes tricky to tune, messy to work with, and hard to plan for.

This year, we are implementing "Absolute Positioning"

This means, we simply give the robot instructions on what coordinates to move to, and the robot will do the rest.

### Execution
We've build a whole class library around this positioning, but here is the block of code that is used to calculate the movements.
```
fun moveTo(x:Double,y:Double){
        val angle = Math.toDegrees(Math.atan((y-currentY)/(x-currentX)))
        val dist = Math.sqrt((x-currentX))*((x-currentX) + (y-currentY))*((y-currentY))
        drivetrain.rotateTo(angle)
        wait(500)
        drivetrain.drive(Direction.FORWARD,dist,timeout=10)
        wait(500)
        registerPosition(x,y,drivetrain.imu.angle)
    }
```
The function takes in an X and Y coordinate in inches, from 0 to 288.
The function then calculates the angle of movement needed using `arctan`
and then it calculates the distance needed to move to that position using Pythagorean Theorem.

Then, it rotates to the desired angle and moves forward the desired distance.
Finally, it registers the new position on the field as the target position so that the next move calculates the desired values from the new position.

### Result
The result of this code is a clean and consice autonomous. Instead of telling the robot to move and turn, we simple tell it the position that we want it to go to.
Thia allows us to write our autonomous in a short amount of lines and also make it easy to debug and edit positions.
